  // Make the PUT call using the fetch API
  const response = await fetch('/api/data', {
    method: 'PUT',
    headers: {
      'Content-Type': 'application/json'
    },
    body: JSON.stringify(data)
  });

  if (!response.ok) {
    throw {
      status: response.status,
      statusText: response.statusText,
      url: response.url,
      message: `HTTP error ${response.status}: ${response.statusText}`
    };
  }

  const result = await response.json();
  // Handle the successful response
} catch (e: HttpError) {
  // Handle the HTTP error
  console.error(`Error ${e.status}: ${e.message}`);
  // You can access other properties of the error object
  console.error(`URL: ${e.url}`);
  console.error(`Status Text: ${e.statusText}`);
}
```

In this example, the `HttpError` interface extends the built-in `Error` interface and includes properties like `status`, `statusText`, and `url`. These properties are commonly available in the response object of a failed HTTP request.

In the `catch` block, we annotate the `e` parameter with the `HttpError` type. This way, TypeScript knows that `e` has the properties defined in the `HttpError` interface, and you can access them safely.

Note that in the `throw` statement inside the `if (!response.ok)` block, we're creating a new object that conforms to the `HttpError` interface and throwing it as an error. This allows us to catch and handle the error with the expected properties in the `catch` block.

You can modify the `HttpError` interface to include any additional properties or methods specific to the HTTP errors you're handling.

To make the catch clause parameter have an unknown type, you can use the `unknown` type in TypeScript. Here's an example:

```typescript
import { HttpError } from './http-error';

try {
  // Make the PUT call using the fetch API
  const response = await fetch('/api/data', {
    method: 'PUT',
    headers: {
      'Content-Type': 'application/json'
    },
    body: JSON.stringify(data)
  });

  if (!response.ok) {
    throw {
      status: response.status,
      statusText: response.statusText,
      url: response.url,
      message: `HTTP error ${response.status}: ${response.statusText}`
    };
  }

  const result = await response.json();
  // Handle the successful response
} catch (e: unknown) {
  // Handle the HTTP error
  if (e instanceof HttpError) {
    console.error(`Error ${e.status}: ${e.message}`);
    console.error(`URL: ${e.url}`);
    console.error(`Status Text: ${e.statusText}`);
  } else {
    console.error('An unexpected error occurred:', e);
  }
}
```

In this example, we annotate the `e` parameter in the `catch` block with the `unknown` type. This means that TypeScript doesn't make any assumptions about the type of `e`, and you need to perform type checks or type assertions before accessing any properties or methods on `e`.

Inside the `catch` block, we use the `instanceof` operator to check if `e` is an instance of the `HttpError` class. If it is, we can safely access the properties of `HttpError` and handle the error accordingly. If `e` is not an instance of `HttpError`, we handle it as an unexpected error and log it to the console.

Using the `unknown` type for the catch clause parameter can be useful when you're not sure about the exact type of the error that might be thrown, or when you want to handle different types of errors in the same catch block.

However, it's important to note that working with the `unknown` type requires additional type checks or type assertions, which can make your code more verbose and potentially harder to maintain. In general, it's recommended to use more specific types whenever possible to benefit from TypeScript's type safety and tooling support.

